Inorder and postorder traversals are not enough to reconstruct a tree from an array, because inorder and postorder traversals only visit vertices in the order in which they are stored in the array. In case of sparse trees, preorder and inorder traversals are not enough; therefore, we need a postorder and inorder traversal to form a tree from an array of sparse trees.

data.sampled: The best case time complexity of the binary tree sort is O(n). This is because the binary tree sort procedure visits each node in the tree depth-first, and for each node, it only needs to compare the left and right sub-trees to determine their relative order. Therefore, the number of visits to each node is either zero or one, and the overall time complexity is dominated by the number of nodes in the tree, which is O(n).
